The '''A686''' is a road in [[Northern England]]. It runs from [[Penrith, Cumbria|Penrith]] in [[Cumbria]] to [[Haydon Bridge]] in [[Northumberland]]. The [[The Automobile Association|AA]] named the A686 ''"One of the Greatest Drives in Britain"'' owing to the dramatic scenery of the [[Pennines]] hills encountered along its route. The road is popular with [[Motorcycling|motorbikers]], and due to the great number of steep bends many casualties occur along the road. It was recently{{when|date=November 2009}} voted 9th best drive in the country by [[Top Gear (magazine)|Top Gear]].{{citation needed|date=November 2009}}

==Route==
The A686 begins at a [[roundabout]] with the [[A66 road (Great Britain)|A66 road]] and [[A6 road (Great Britain)|A6 road]] on the edge of Penrith though it originally started in nearby [[Carleton village|Carleton]] at a crossroads with the former route of the A66. The road heads in a north-easterly direction crossing the [[River Eden, Cumbria|River Eden]] before going through the village of [[Langwathby]]. It continues through [[Melmerby, Cumbria|Melmerby]] and across the [[Pennines]] before reaching the isolated market town of [[Alston, Cumbria|Alston]].

It meets the [[A689 road]] (to [[Brampton, Carlisle, Cumbria|Brampton]] and [[Bishop Auckland]]) and then crosses the border into [[Northumberland]]. It continues past the villages of [[Ninebanks]], [[Bearsbridge]] and [[Whitfield, Northumberland|Whitfield]]. It meets the B6305 road to [[Hexham]], and {{convert|3.1|mi}} later terminates at its junction with the [[A69 road (Great Britain)|A69 road]] just east of Haydon Bridge.

