An '''intertidal wetland''' is an area along a shoreline that is exposed to [[air]] at [[low tide]] and submerged at [[high tide]]. This type of [[wetland]] is defined by an [[intertidal zone]] and includes its own [[intertidal ecosystem]]s.

==Description==
The main types of intertidal wetlands are [[mudflat]]s (e.g., [[mangrove swamp]]s) and [[salt marsh]]es. The mangrove swamps are encountered along [[tropical]] shores and are characterized by [[tree]] vegetation, while  salt marshes are mostly found in [[temperate]] zones and are mostly [[grass]] ecosystems.<ref name=dya/>

Intertidal wetlands are commonly encountered in most [[estuaries]]. Intertidal wetland [[ecosystem]]s are amongst the most productive plant communities and often constitute a large part of the estuary areas.<ref name=dya>''Estuarine Ecology'', by John W. Day, Alejandro Yáñez-Arancibia, Chapter 5: [https://books.google.com/books?id=Pn1x9wk-u1sC&pg=PA188&dq=%22intertidal+wetlands%22 Intertidal Wetlands: Salt Marshes and Mangrove Swamps]</ref>

