[[File:Newtownards Town Hall - geograph.org.uk - 466808.jpg|right|250px]] '''Market House''' in [[Newtownards]], [[County Down]], [[Northern Ireland]], is a historic building. It was built during 1767-1771<ref>[https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC27HPQ_newtownards-historical-series-9-the-market-house?guid=92e77800-b15f-47eb-9a76-b1b9ac4107d9 Newtownards Historical Series #9 The Market House]</ref> by [[Robert Stewart, 1st Marquess of Londonderry]] to be the center of the market town, in lieu of the [[Newtownards Priory]].<ref>[http://ulsterscotstrail.com/newtownards/market-house Ulster Scots Heritage Trail: Market House]</ref>It has served as a prison and as a [[town hall]]. It is currently the '''Newtownards Arts Centre''' is also the home of the [[Ards Historical Society]].
It was built of [[Scrabo stone]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.culturenorthernireland.org/features/heritage/history-newtownards |title=The History of Newtownards |publisher=Culture Northern Ireland}}</ref>
Standing at the north end of Conway Square in Newtownards' town centre, the Market House was built in 1770s to a design of Ferdinando Stratford, a bridge and river engineer from [[Bristol]] in England. The ground floor was originally an open space where a market could be held and was entered from Conway Square through a central archway which was fitted with gates that could be opened and closed at night. The upper floor had an assembly room over the west wing with a drawing room in the east wing, now known as the Londonderry Room.
Originally the market was held inside the market house, but the tradition which remains today and is now held outside in Conway Square each Saturday.
[[File:Town Hall, Newtownards - geograph.org.uk - 643446.jpg|left|thumb]] The Market House was also used as a military base during the [[Irish Rebellion of 1798|1798 Rebellion against British rule]], housing a regiment of the York [[Fencibles]] under the command of Colonel Stapleton. Prison cells which were on either side of the archway and can be seen today from inside the ground floor of the building. Many years later the Market House was used as the local Town Hall, but today it is used as an Arts Centre. The drawing room on the upper floor (now the Londonderry Room) is still used for meetings and exhibitions.
