{{Main|Public Land Survey System}} [[File:Beginning Point of the U.S. Public Land Survey front.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Marker for the Beginning Point of the U.S. Public Land Survey]] The '''point of beginning''' is a [[Surveyor (surveying)|surveyor]]'s mark at the beginning location for the wide-scale surveying of land.
An example is the [[Beginning Point of the U.S. Public Land Survey]] that led to the opening of the [[Northwest Territory]], and is the starting point of the surveys of almost all other lands to the west, reaching all the way to the [[Pacific Ocean]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tps.cr.nps.gov/nhl/detail.cfm?ResourceId=441&ResourceType=Site|title=Beginning Point of the U.S. Public Land Survey|accessdate=2007-11-08|work=National Historic Landmark summary listing|publisher=National Park Service|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071023013601/http://tps.cr.nps.gov/nhl/detail.cfm?ResourceId=441&ResourceType=Site|archivedate=2007-10-23|df=}}</ref> On September 30, 1785, [[Thomas Hutchins]], first and only Geographer of the United States,<ref>[http://www.profsurv.com/magazine/article.aspx?i=70281 Fort Steuben History]</ref> began surveying the [[Seven Ranges]] at the point of beginning.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Witcher |first=T. R. |date=July-August 2018 |title=Setting the Boundaries: The Point of Beginning Survey |url=https://www.asce.org/uploadedFiles/CE_Magazine/Home_Page/Content_Pieces/2018-7-8-history-lesson--setting-the-boundaries.pdf |magazine=Civil Engineering |location=Reston, Va. |publisher=American Society of Civil Engineers |access-date=August 4, 2018}}</ref>
==Points of beginning== * [[Beginning Point of the U.S. Public Land Survey]] – [[East Liverpool, Ohio]] * [http://www.uwgb.edu/dutchs/GeologyWisconsin/geostops/Point%20of%20Beginning.HTM Point of Beginning in Wisconsin]
